entry.title: FLEDGE: Hold ref to DebugCommandQueue from IOSession.
entry.content:
IOSession held a raw pointer to DebugCommandQueue, which could end up dangling --- DebugCommandQueue is mostly-owned by AuctionV8Helper, while IOSession is normally controlled by its pipe, so it's really hard to say when it will actually get deleted, given lack of ordering guarantees on mojo pipes. Luckily DebugCommandQuue is already ref-counted and doesn't hold much itself (just a thread runner ref), so we can have IOSession co-own it.



(Thanks to miracle ptr for pointing out the problem).

entry.title: [Tailored Security] Prevent running retry in the unset state case
entry.content:
Add a guard for the kTailoredSecuritySyncFlowRetryState is UNSET case.

This case is intended to help in the casees where an older version of

Chrome ran for the user, and it failed. We know that if

kEnhancedProtectionEnabledViaTailoredSecurity is set, then the user has

been shown the Tailored Security dialogs in the past.



By adding an additional condition that

kEnhancedProtectionEnabledViaTailoredSecurity hasn't been set, we can

further target only retrying for users where a very old version of

Chrome may have run the logic (pre-M106) or a post-M106 Chrome ran, and

never succeeded at showing the dialog to the user.

entry.title: Wire up Capture process frame drops to MediaStreamVideoTrack.
entry.content:
This CL wires up the frame drop callback from the source (which is

aware of Capture process frame drops) to the VideoTrackAdapter, and

makes the VideoAdapter invoke DoNotifyFrameDropped() which is already

wired up to MediaStreamVideoTrack.



This means that the MediaStreamVideoTrack is now aware of all frame

drops, not just the frame drops happening inside VideoTrackAdapter. The

track treats all frame drops the same and does not care if it happened

early or late in the pipeline. This means it is included in the

MediaStreamTrack Statistics API.



This is unit test-covered using a fake source to signal frame drops.



As for end-to-end testing, I have also manually verified that calling

VideoFrameReceiver::OnFrameDropped() inside the Capture process

results in `track.stats.totalFrames` incrementing in JavaScript. This

is unfortunately not testable in Web Platform Tests because fake

sources are not available to JS, and under normal circumstances frames

are flowing without drops.

sources that don't have frame dropping can ignore the callback.

entry.title: [iOS] Re-write account cookie waiting
entry.content:
This patch is a reland of crrev.com/c/4766696. I believe the patch

was reverted for flakiness not related to the patch.

ios-simulator-full-confgs bot was able to run 4 times without issues.

The original patch is in patchset 1.



No behaviour change for most practical cases. The CL might also be a

bug fix for some speculative scenarios, more details below.



Context: When accounts.google.com is opened, a bottom sheet is shown

to offer browser sign in. If the user taps its primary button, the

sheet waits until the account cookie is populated, then closes itself.

It might also show an error dialog instead, in case of an auth error or

timeout.



Before this CL, this was implemented as follows:

1. ConsistencyPromoSigninMediator observed the IdentityManager for

its entire lifetime.

2. Upon getting an OnAccountsInCookieUpdated() notification, it

checked whether a) there was no auth error, b) there was a primary

account, and c) the cookie jar was non-empty. If all 3 were

satisfied, it closed the sheet.



This approach has some problems, at least theoretically.

- In 1, more than one notification might arrive. Or a notification

might arrive before the user taps the button.

- In 2, the check is still satisfied if the cookie jar is filled with

an account different from the one selected by the user in the UI.



This CL:

- Extracts the waiting logic to a helper class.

- Checks that cookie jar for the correct account.

entry.title: [ios] Fix animation glitch when restoring session
entry.content:
With change https://crrev.com/c/4852091, the active WebState is

inserted with the `INSERT_ACTIVATE` flag. This causes the item

to immediately become the active WebState upon insertion.



FullscreenWebStateListObserver is exiting the fullscreen mode

when the active WebState change. The use of `INSERT_ACTIVATE`

flag meant that the call to `ExitFullscreen()` occurred while

the WebState was inserted in the WebStateList.



However since the WebState view has not yet been inserted at this

point, this resulted in an animation starting with a size of (0; 0)

and ending with the final size.



To prevent this glitch use ExitFullscreenWithoutAnimation() to

exit the fullscreen mode when a batch operation is in progress

(which is likely related to session restoration).



Fixed: 1485930

change tickled due to the change to the tests creating buffers via

entry.title: Reapply "[//cc] Add MappableSI path to OneCopyRasterBufferProvider"
entry.content:
This CL adds a new path to OneCopyRasterBufferProvider that uses

MappableSharedImage rather than GpuMemoryBuffer. The new path is

protected by a base::Feature that is disabled by default. The gist of

the change is that rather than creating a GpuMemoryBuffer, mapping that

in, and then later creating a SharedImage from it, the new path directly

creates a MappableSharedImage (via the new CreateSI() entrypoint), maps

that in, *and* additionally uses it in the same ways that the SI created

from the GMB is being used.



One subtlety is that the GMB is created with the size of the

StagingBuffer, while the SharedImage for the StagingBuffer in its

current creation point in CopyOnWorkerThread() is created with the

`resource_size` param passed to PlaybackAndCopyOnWorkerThread(). Thus,

we would want the MappableSI for the StagingBuffer to be created with

"both" sizes. Fortunately (and as one would expect), the StagingBuffer

is initialized with the `resource_size` param, so the two sizes are

guaranteed to be the same [1].



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:cc/raster/one_copy_raster_buffer_provider.cc;l=295-297?q=CopyOnWorker&ss=chromium



NOTE: This CL is a reland. The only difference from the original is that

the base::Feature is disabled rather than enabled while we investigate

test issues that might have been caused by this CL as well as

performance regressions flagged by Pinpoint.

entry.title: [Privacy Sandbox] Add UMA metric for time taken for attestations file
entry.content:
becomes ready.



PS APIs will be required to be attested to be used. See

https://github.com/privacysandbox/attestation



The goal of the metrics is to help us understand the gap between the

use of Privacy Sandbox APIs and the time attestations map is ready.

The attestations map is used to check whether the site that an API is

concerned is attested or not.



The attestations map is obtained by parsing the attestations file

downloaded by the component updater. The parsing starts when

ComponentReady() is called. Since the parsing time is relatively short.

We would like to measure the time elapsed before ComponentReady() call.



There are three possible time points ComponentReady() gets called.



Timeline:

1. User opens browser.

2. *Possible ComponentReady call* If there is existing component on

disk from previous runs, and the priority used by registration is

USER_VISIBLE. This happens immediately after browser starts.

3. Possible non-browser UI shows, e.g, profile picker.

4. *Possible ComponentReady call* If user stays at non-browser UI for

a long time. After about 4 minutes, ComponentReady is called if there

is existing file on disk. If no existing file on disk, and the

priority is BEST_EFFORT, the ComponentReady() will not be called.

5. Non-browser UI is closed. Browser window first paint takes place.

6. *Possible ComponentReady call* If user doesn't stay at

the non-browser UI for a long time, or there is no non-browser UI.

This can be a fresh install, or a re-install from existing file.



Added three histograms for each case. For each session, at most one of

the three histogram will be recorded.



Note: Even if I have all UMA strings in privacy_sandbox_attestations_histograms.h. In startup_metric_utils.cc,

I still hardcode all of them instead of using the include file. This

is because the trybot is not happy when I include: crbug.com/1468362.

entry.title: [FPS] Stop checking is_internal before computing FPS metadata
entry.content:
Currently, if the browser is started in minimal mode (as is the case

for some Android tests), the component updater system is not started

(even though the kDisableComponentUpdate flag is not enabled).

Additionally, First-Party Sets itself is not initialized (Init is not called). So, most web requests will be paused indefinitely and will

never complete. This does not cause a problem at ToT since *internal*

web requests (those that use an IsolationInfo that does not fill in a

party_context) are *not* paused (due to the condition in

cookie_util.cc), and apparently no tests start the browser in minimal

mode and then issue a non-internal web request.



It would be good to avoid this special case, so that more web requests

are handled identically w.r.t. First-Party Sets. To do this, we can

remove the check of is_internal (since is_internal is no longer

required by FPS, anyway). We also make some changes to properly

initialize First-Party Sets when the browser is running in minimal

mode, including introducing a bool to ContentBrowserClient to

distinguish minimal mode and full browser mode. (It does feel slightly

wrong to make ContentBrowserClient stateful, but I haven't found a

better solution, and ChromeContentBrowserClient is stateful so there's

sort of a precedent.)



Note that at least one Android test starts the browser in minimal mode

and then upgrades to full browser mode (without restarting), so we

adjust the First-Party Sets initialization to be idempotent and allow

multiple calls to Init.

entry.title: Change the way account id is seeded.
entry.content:
Per stack trace in crbug.com/1482236, method

AuthenticationService::OnApplicationWillEnterForeground() is seeding

empty account ids in some cases. The explanation comes from the way

the account id is computed for an identity stored in the cache of

MDM errors before reloading the accounts.



This CL updates the logic used to compute the account id from an

SystemIdentity and ensure that this does not depend on whether the

identity is present in the identity manager already or not. It also

avoid seeding accounts that had MDM errors if they are not already

present in the identity manager.

entry.title: Switch RuleMap to a custom hash table.
entry.content:
A significant part of style (~6%) is doing lookups in RuleMaps,

specifically in AtomicString-indexed hash tables. These currently

use WTF::HashTable, but we can do better with a custom

hash table implementation. Thus, we implement RobinHoodMap,

a lookup-optimized variant with higher load factor and thus

tighter memory footprint.



One direct consequence of this is less RAM usage; e.g. Social1

reports ~460 kB less PartitionAlloc memory allocated (most subtests

have smaller hash tables, though, since they have fewer rules).

But we also get less cache pressure. The exact result depends

on the CPU; smaller/slower caches give more gains, less sophisticated

branch predictors give less gains. In general, most seem to be

around neutral, but Intel CPUs give a fairly good gain. Inserts

are slightly slower and lookups are faster, so repeated style

application should get larger gains. Of course, in the style

perftest, we have the cache all to ourselves, so it will tend to

underestimate these effects somewhat.

entry.title: Forward Capture process frame drops to Renderer process.
entry.content:
The MediaStreamTrack is currently unaware of what the camera's frame

rate is, because if a frame is dropped in the Capture process this is

never forwarded to the track. This is a problem for the implementation

of the MediaStreamTrack Statistics API, which currently counts delivered

frames correctly but not dropped frames.



The MediaStreamTrackImpl aims to count all frames that are dropped, but

is currently only aware of frames that were dropped in the Renderer

process. These frame drops are signalled to the Browser process'

VideoCaptureController where UMAs are counted.



The VideoCaptureController also received signals about frame drops in

the Capture process. This CL makes the controller forward frame drops

that originated in the Capture process to the Renderer process (but does

not forward frame drops that happened in the Renderer process, since the

Renderer process is already aware of these).



See diagram: https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/attachment?aid=613344&signed_aid=qgr6SdlcmdfuTpNMqHyzFQ==&inline=1



In the future, when MediaStreamTrackImpl is aware of all frame drops,

we can move the UMAs to MediaStreamTrackImpl and delete the frame drop

callbacks that are reported from Renderer -> Browser processes. This

would make all frame drop signals go in a single direction:

Capture -> Browser -> Renderer



In a follow-up CL we will continue to plumb the frame drop signal until

it reaches MediaStreamTrackImpl.

entry.title: [iOS] Fix invariant on SignInAndHistorySyncCoordinator interruption
entry.content:
SigninCoordinator expects the identity in the completion info (argument

of the coordinator completion call back) to be nil if the coordinator

was interrupted before the sign-in flow is completed. And it should be

the case even if a sign-in is finished. (for instance in

TwoScreensSigninCoordinator).



However, the new SignInAndHistorySyncCoordinator uses the signed-in

identity instead of nil in this case, which triggers the

DCHECK in SigninCoordinator's runCompletionCallbackWithSigninResult.



To keep consistency with existing Signincoordinator, this CL set the

identity to nil during interruption.

entry.title: [mullet m2] Save profile changes and re-open the Autofill prompt.
entry.content:
User changes should be saved to the existing Autofill profile after the

"Save" button is clicked. The Autofill prompt should be opened again

after the user closes the edit dialog by clicking either "Cancel" or

"Save button.



Reopening the Autofill popup relies on the fact that the editor callback

is invoked when the editor dialog window is closed. If the Autofill

profile is going to be updated through the PersonalDataManager, the

caller must make sure the Autofill popup is triggered only once the

update is finished as it's an async task. This is achieved by adding

a PersonalDataManagerObserver to the PersonalDataManager and reopening

the prompt only once the update process has finished.



ContentAutofillDriver::RendererShouldTriggerSuggestions is invoked to

make the renderer process reopen the Autofill prompt. This is done to

ensure that the suggestions are regenerated from scratch and the regular

code path is used to trigger the popup.

entry.title: [Sync][Cleanup] Refactor SyncerError
entry.content:
SyncerError used to mostly replicate SyncProtocolErrorType and mixed in

few other unrelated enum values, this CL makes some adjustments to avoid

this:

1. SyncProtocolErrorType extended with commit-specific values (CONFLICT,

INVALID_MESSAGE).

2. SyncerError stores high-level enum (success, network error, http

error, protocol error, protocol violation) + details specific to the

error type.

3. HTTP_UNAUTHORIZED is no longer special cased as a dedicated enum

value (callers check http status code when they need to special case

it).

4. UNSET has no analogues in the new SyncerError. Success() is used as

a default value (their treatments where equivalent, see IsActualError()

in old SyncerError).



There should be no behavioral changes, except some strings in

chrome://sync-internals.
